<div xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><head>Report:</head><p>Zinc oxide (ZnO) plays an active role in many catalytic reactions, such as methanol synthesis and the water gas shift. <ref type="bibr" target="#b0">[1]</ref>. Determination of the stable ZnO surface structure and studies of how it interacts with the gases is essential for understanding these catalytic processes, where the detailed reaction mechanisms are under current discussion <ref type="bibr" target="#b1">[2]</ref>. The non-polar, vicinal, ZnO(10-14) surface has recently been suggested to be a stable facet of ZnO( <ref type="formula">0001</ref>) and (000-1) <ref type="bibr" target="#b2">[3,</ref><ref type="bibr" target="#b3">4]</ref>. During the beamtime we for the first time studied a vicinal ZnO(10-14) single crystal with the aim to determine the structure of the vicinal surface, as well as its stability and structure after water exposure.</p></div>
			</abstract>
		</profileDesc>
